3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly Network calculates funding rates hourly based on the premium between perpetual and spot prices across its shared order book. The platform's unique architecture aggregates trading activity from multiple frontend partners on NEAR and EVM chains, creating funding rate dynamics that reflect cross-chain arbitrage pressure. Settlement occurs automatically every hour with rates applied to open positions, while the shared liquidity model can create temporary rate discrepancies as arbitrageurs move between different frontend interfaces accessing the same underlying order book."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","W","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"W/USDT represents infrastructure token exposure on a multi-chain DEX architecture, making it particularly sensitive to cross-chain arbitrage flows and liquidity fragmentation. The pair's funding rates often reflect broader infrastructure narrative cycles and can exhibit extended periods of positive or negative funding as traders position for network adoption trends across NEAR and Ethereum ecosystems."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"W/USDT funding rates on Orderly Network have shown distinct patterns tied to infrastructure development cycles and cross-chain adoption waves. During periods of NEAR ecosystem growth, the pair often exhibits sustained positive funding as long positions accumulate, while broader market corrections can trigger negative funding lasting several days. The shared liquidity model means funding rates are influenced by activity across all connected frontends, creating smoother rate transitions compared to isolated DEX platforms. Quarterly funding rate averages typically range from -0.05% to +0.15% depending on infrastructure narrative strength and cross-chain bridge activity."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Cross-Chain Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly's multi-chain architecture creates unique arbitrage opportunities between W/USDT funding rates and equivalent positions on single-chain platforms. Traders can exploit rate differentials by holding opposite positions across Orderly's shared book and CEX platforms, particularly during periods of high cross-chain transaction costs. The platform's 0.02% maker fees and hourly settlements enable profitable arbitrage on rate differences as small as 0.1% daily. Bridge delays between NEAR and EVM chains can extend arbitrage windows, making Orderly particularly attractive for longer-duration funding rate strategies targeting infrastructure token volatility."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Trading W/USDT funding rates on Orderly Network requires careful attention to cross-chain execution risks and frontend dependency. The shared order book model means liquidity can vary significantly depending on which frontends are active, potentially affecting position entry and exit timing during volatile periods. Smart contract risks exist across multiple chains, while the platform's reliance on frontend partners creates counterparty considerations not present on traditional DEX platforms. Funding rate arbitrageurs should monitor bridge health across NEAR and EVM chains, as cross-chain failures can trap positions and eliminate arbitrage exit strategies during critical market movements."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Orderly Network's shared order book affect W/USDT funding rates?","answer":"The shared order book aggregates trading activity from multiple DEX frontends, creating more stable funding rates than isolated platforms. However, this can also mean rates respond more slowly to sudden market changes as they reflect consensus across the entire federated network rather than individual platform dynamics."},{"question":"Can I arbitrage W/USDT funding rates between different Orderly frontends?","answer":"No, all frontends access the same underlying order book and funding rate calculation, so rates are identical across all Orderly-powered platforms. Arbitrage opportunities exist between Orderly as a whole and external exchanges, not between different Orderly frontends."},{"question":"What are the main risks of cross-chain funding arbitrage with W/USDT?","answer":"Primary risks include bridge delays that can trap positions during volatile periods, frontend dependency where interface issues could affect trade execution, and smart contract risks across multiple chains. Cross-chain transaction costs can also erode arbitrage profits during periods of network congestion."},{"question":"How do Orderly's hourly settlements compare to 8-hour funding on CEX platforms?","answer":"Hourly settlements provide more frequent profit realization and position adjustment opportunities compared to 8-hour CEX cycles. This allows for more responsive arbitrage strategies but requires active monitoring as funding accumulates more frequently, making position management more intensive."}]}]
